			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I'm in a guild where there usually are enough LFG people to coax over to a zone for 30 minutes to help with an epic. We have the blessing of having an epic most people haven't seen done before, so the curiosity factor works wonders. When you further explain "just you and I can do this mob!" they're usually impressed (implied flattery too at how much a difference they can make)!
<br />

<br />
Common comments after doing one of the epic mobs:
<br />
"That was easy, are there any more we can do?"
<br />
"How many left?"
<br />
"That was fun."
<br />
"Why can't my epic be this simple?"
<br />
"Glad to have helped."
<br />
"Ask me anytime you need help with the next one."
<br />
"Wow this was quick!"
<br />

<br />
I have sent tells to LFG clerics and shammies and others I've never met before, asking politely if they would be interested in helping. I tend to include in that tell how much time needed, what zone, what level of mob, and what problem (AE or whatever) it represents.
<br />

<br />
Big note for getting people's attention when doing this: No shorthand. "Plz" and "can u hlp?" don't cut it. Typing out a correctly spelled, grammatically correct and POLITE request will really make a good impression.
<br />

<br />
Also, I never once promised a bribe of cash, items, or loot. And actually I wasn't even asked about it. It's good form to donate peridots to enchanters and clerics that help you, but in my case I was always rushed and broke so never even did that.<br />_________________<br />-Zoransis Thule, Beastlord of Luclin</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
